{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505483"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.02,0.02,0.09,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82568"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2446"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67733"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2852"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6347"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1990"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82568"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of worsening pain and swelling of his left knee. The pain is now so severe he has difficulty walking. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and takes metformin. He smokes 20 cigarettes per day and drinks two standard drinks of alcohol daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 111/min, blood pressure 110/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His left knee is tender, warm, and erythematous with marked swelling and decreased range of motion. Several needle marks are noted on his left arm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnetic resonance imaging of the knee","Plain radiograph of the knee","C-reactive protein measurement","Blood cultures","Synovial fluid aspiration"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious for septic arthritis, including an acutely hot, swollen, and painful joint with systemic symptoms. He has multiple risk factors including diabetes mellitus and likely intravenous drug use - given the case stem description of needle track marks. Prompt diagnosis and treatment are essential to prevent joint destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynovial fluid aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it provides crucial diagnostic information through cell count, microscopy, Gram stain and culture. This should be performed before starting antibiotics to maximise the chance of identifying the causative organism, most commonly \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. Normal synovial fluid is clear with white cell count less than 200/mm3, while in septic arthritis the fluid is typically cloudy with white cell count greater than 50,000/mm3. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E of the knee is not indicated as the initial investigation. While it can show detailed joint changes including synovitis, effusion, and cartilage destruction, it would delay the essential step of obtaining synovial fluid for culture. MRI may be useful later if there is diagnostic uncertainty or to assess the extent of joint damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain radiograph\u003C/strong\u003E of the knee may show joint effusion or destruction in late disease but is not sensitive for early septic arthritis. It would not provide the crucial microbiological information needed for diagnosis and treatment. However, it may be useful to exclude underlying osteomyelitis or to document pre-existing joint disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E should be taken but are not as important as synovial fluid cultures, as they may be negative even in the presence of septic arthritis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E measurement, while useful in monitoring the response to treatment, is not specific enough to diagnose septic arthritis and should not delay joint aspiration. Other inflammatory markers like erythrocyte sedimentation rate and white cell count are similarly non-specific but may help track treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining synovial fluid, empiric antibiotics should be started immediately. The choice of antibiotics should cover \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (including methicillin-resistant strains in high-risk patients) and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species. Urgent orthopaedic consultation is required as most patients will need surgical washout.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Synovial fluid aspiration for microscopy and culture is the essential first investigation in suspected septic arthritis","Risk factors for septic arthritis include diabetes, intravenous drug use, immunosuppression and prosthetic joints","Delay in diagnosis and treatment of septic arthritis can lead to permanent joint destruction","Normal synovial fluid is clear with WCC \u003C200/mm3; septic arthritis typically shows cloudy fluid with WCC \u003E50,000/mm3"],"references":["Coakley G, Mathews C, Field M, Jones A, Kingsley G, Walker D, Phillips M, Bradish C, McLachlan A, Mohammed R, Weston V; British Society for Rheumatology Standards, Guidelines and Audit Working Group. BSR \u0026 BHPR, BOA, RCGP and BSAC guidelines for management of the hot swollen joint in adults. Rheumatology (Oxford). 2006 Aug;45(8):1039-41.","Turner, E.H.G., Lang, M.D.H. \u0026 Spiker, A.M. A narrative review of the last decade\u2019s literature on the diagnostic accuracy of septic arthritis of the native joint. J EXP ORTOP 8, 3 (2021). https://doi.org/10.1186/s40634-020-00315-w"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67733"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67733"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T22:41:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T22:42:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2446"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82568"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta